  "footnotes": [
    "Basques: the only pre-Indo-European people of Western Europe to preserve their language into the modern era; their origin is uncertain (possibly Mesolithic Iberian survivors); they maintained practical autonomy through most of Roman, Visigothic, and medieval Spanish rule due to their mountain strongholds in the Pyrenees",
    "Byzantine Spania (554–624 CE): the Eastern Roman Empire exploited Visigothic dynastic conflicts to land an army in southeastern Spain in 554 under Athanagild; the province included Cartagena, Málaga, and parts of Baetica; it was gradually reconquered by the Visigothic King Suinthila, who expelled the Byzantines by 624",
    "Caliphate of Córdoba (929–1031): Abd al-Rahman III's proclamation of the Caliphate made Córdoba the largest city in Europe (estimated population 500,000); his library reportedly held 400,000 volumes; the court hosted scholars from across the Islamic world and tolerantly employed Christians (mozarabes) and Jews in administration",
    "County of Portugal (868–1139): created as a frontier county of the Kingdom of León; the county was given to Count Henry of Burgundy in 1095 as a reward for Crusade service; his son Afonso Henriques declared Portuguese independence after the Battle of Ourique (1139), recognized by León in 1143",
    "Iberian Union (1580–1640): Philip II of Spain inherited Portugal after the childless death of King Sebastião in the Battle of Alcácer Quibir (1578); the union was accepted by Portuguese elites under the condition of administrative separation; the Portuguese Restoration War (1640–1668) reestablished independence under the Braganza dynasty",
    "Carnation Revolution (25 April 1974): a nearly bloodless military coup by the Armed Forces Movement ended 48 years of the Estado Novo dictatorship; soldiers placed carnations in their rifle barrels; the revolution triggered rapid decolonization of Portugal's African empire (Angola, Mozambique, Guinea-Bissau) and transition to parliamentary democracy"
  ]
}
